<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="hw3">
  <title>📝 Homework 3</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            <alert>Instructions:</alert> This assignment is due <alert>Wednesday, July 8</alert>. Write solutions to the following problems in the space provided. If you need additional space, you may attach scratch work to the back of this sheet. Please be sure any additional work is clearly labeled with the question it corresponds to.
        </p>
    </introduction>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        The amount <m>A</m> of a radioactive substance after <m>t</m> years decays proportionally to itself. That is <md>
            \dfrac{dA}{dt} \propto -A.
        </md>
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Write a first-order linear differential equation that models the radioactive decay of a substance assuming their is an initial amount <m>A_0</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the solution to the differential equation in your model. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <alert>half-life</alert> of a radioactive substance is the amount of time it takes to lose half of its mass (amount). Use your model to derive a formula for the half-life of a radioactive substance. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="3in">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Two large containers <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> of the same size are filled with different fluids. Container <m>A</m>'s fluid is held at <m>0^\circ</m>C and container <m>B</m>'s fluid is held at <m>100^\circ</m>C. A small metal bar is brought to <m>100^\circ</m>C, then submerged into container <m>A</m>. Its temperature is measured 1 minute later to be <m>90^\circ</m>C. After 1 more minute (2 minutes from its inital plunge), it is transfered to container <m>B</m>. The temperature of the bar rises by <m>10^\circ</m>C after 1 miunute in container <m>B</m>. If the bar is left in container <m>B</m>, how long will it take the bar to reach <m>99.9^\circ</m>C? 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            A local fishery can hold at most 500 fish. But, the fish naturally reproduce by 500 fish per month. The fishery avoids overcrowding by stocking local lakes and rivers with 400 fish per month. Let <m>P</m> denote the number of fish after <m>t</m> months.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Assuming the fish grow logistically, find the growth function <m>f(P)</m> such that <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = f(P)</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the differential equation <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = f(P)</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="3in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Draw a phase portrait for the model. Plot and label all nullclines on your phase portrait. Label each nullcline as stable of unstable. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>

    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                What is the minimum number of fish the fishery should have at the beginning of the season to avoid extinction? 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Verify that <md> u(t) = c_1 \cos(t) + c_2 \sin(t) + t \sin(t) + \cos(t) \ln(t) </md> is the general solution to the nonhomogeneous equation <md> u'' + u = (2-t^{-2})\cos(t) - 2t^{-1}\sin(t) </md> on the interval <m> (-\pi / 2, \pi / 2) </m>, then label its fundamental, complementary, and particular solutions. 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>
